==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Found
<hw>Found</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Founded</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Founding</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[F. <ets>fonder</ets>, L.
<ets>fundare</ets>, fr. <ets>fundus</ets> bottom. See 1st
<er>Bottom</er>, and cf. <er>Founder</er>, <pos>v. i.</pos>,
<er>Fund</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To lay the basis of; to set, or
place, as on something solid, for support; to ground; to establish upon
a basis, literal or figurative; to fix firmly.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I had else been perfect,⟦br⟧
Whole as the marble, <qex>founded</qex> as the rock.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A man that all his time⟦br⟧
Hath <qex>founded</qex> his good fortunes on your love.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>It fell not, for it was <qex>founded</qex> on a rock.</q>
<rj><qau>Matt. vii. 25.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To take the ffirst steps or measures in erecting or
building up; to furnish the materials for beginning; to begin to raise;
to originate; <as>as, to <ex>found</ex> a college; to <ex>found</ex> a
family.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>There they shall <qex>found</qex>⟦br⟧
Their government, and their great senate choose.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj></p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To base; ground; institute; establish; fix. See
<er>Predicate</er>.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Foundation</ent>⟦br⟧
